    <%= render "shared/calculator_rating", slug: "college-cost-comparison" %>
    <div class="mb-8"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_results" %></div>

    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the College Cost Comparison Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Enter the annual tuition, room and board, fees, and financial aid for two colleges to see a complete side-by-side cost comparison. The calculator accounts for annual cost inflation, which typically runs 3-5% for higher education, providing a realistic total cost projection over your full enrollment period. Financial aid is kept constant each year, reflecting the typical structure of renewable scholarships and grants.
      </p>
      <p>
        Use the net price rather than the sticker price for the most accurate comparison. Every college in the United States is required to have a net price calculator on its website, which provides personalized estimates based on your family's financial situation. The difference between sticker price and net price can be dramatic, especially at private institutions that offer generous institutional aid.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Factors Beyond Tuition to Consider</h2>
      <p>
        The true cost of college extends beyond tuition and room and board. Consider textbooks and supplies (averaging $1,200-$1,400 per year), transportation costs (especially if the school is far from home), personal expenses, and opportunity costs. Students at more expensive schools may need to work fewer hours if they receive better financial aid, which can lead to better academic performance and higher graduation rates.
      </p>

      <h3>The Hidden Value of Financial Aid Packages</h3>
      <p>
        Not all financial aid is created equal. Grants and scholarships are free money, while loans must be repaid with interest. A college offering $30,000 in aid with $20,000 in grants and $10,000 in loans is a better deal than one offering $30,000 entirely in loans. Work-study positions provide valuable work experience but require your time. Break down each aid package by type to understand your true financial obligation.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What costs should I include when comparing colleges?</h3>
      <p>Include tuition, mandatory fees, room and board (or estimated living expenses for commuters), books and supplies, transportation, and personal expenses. Subtract any grants, scholarships, and tuition waivers to get the net cost.</p>

      <h3>How does financial aid affect total college cost?</h3>
      <p>Financial aid from grants and scholarships directly reduces your out-of-pocket cost each year. Renewable scholarships provide consistent savings across all four years, while one-time awards only reduce costs in the year received.</p>

      <h3>Why does college cost inflation matter?</h3>
      <p>College costs have historically risen 3-5% annually, faster than general inflation. A school charging $30,000 today could cost over $33,000 by your senior year.</p>

      <h3>Should I choose the cheapest college?</h3>
      <p>Not necessarily. Consider the return on investment including average starting salaries for graduates, employment rates, program quality, networking opportunities, and quality of life.</p>

      <h3>What is the difference between sticker price and net price?</h3>
      <p>Sticker price is the published tuition and fees before any financial aid. Net price is what you actually pay after subtracting grants, scholarships, and education tax benefits.</p>

      <%= render "shared/print_button" %>
      <%= render "shared/calculation_email_capture" %>
    </article>

